  "title": "react-native and react compatible highlight method",
  "body": "<!--\r\n  Thanks for participating in this project!\r\n  Please:\r\n    - make sure you are using the latest version of the library.\r\n    - do at least one GitHub search in current issues, maybe your question is already here\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**\r\nfeature\r\n\r\n**What is the current behavior?**\r\nRight now we have a highlighting helper method that you can use like this:\r\n\r\n```jsx\r\nfunction Product({hit}) {\r\n  return (\r\n    <div>\r\n      <span className=\"hit-name\">{highlight('name', hit)}</span>\r\n    </div>\r\n  );\r\n};\r\n```\r\n\r\nGiven query is \"co\" and `name` is \"coca\", it will generate this:\r\n\r\n```html\r\n<div>\r\n  <span className=\"hit-name\">\r\n  <em className=\"ais-highlightedValue\" key=\"split-0-co\">co</em>ca\r\n  </span>\r\n</div>\r\n```\r\n\r\n**What is the expected behavior?**\r\n\r\nThis is the only API entry we provide for highlighting. What if:\r\n- I want to use another tag than `<em/>`\r\n- I am not using the default theme and thus I don't want the classNames etc\r\n- I am using react-native\r\n\r\nThen you cannot really use this.\r\n\r\n**Proposal**\r\n\r\n```js\r\nhighlight({\r\n  tagName:,\r\n  pathToAttribute: 'desc.name'\r\n  hit:,\r\n  props: {\r\n  \r\n  }\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nAs for having a specific widget for react-native, since we do not have any widget and I am not skilled into native, I have no proposal.",
